Hi Rob,

the latest version of MultiNEAT allows the genomes to have evolvable 
traits independent of the node/link graph. Check out the GitHub 
repository. The TestTraits.py file in contains the example code that 
shows how to use the functionality (alongside evolving arbitrary traits 
for nodes and links).

Peter

On 07/17/2017 11:49 PM, rob rob@... [neat] wrote:
&gt;
&gt; I&#39;m using the MultiNEAT library to solve a couple of problems that
&gt; would seem to be disparate in nature, but, both require facilities that
&gt; lie outside of NEAT.
&gt;
&gt; The first manages a batch chemical process and controls the optimal
&gt; yield cut-off point. The second manages a portfolio of currencies held
&gt; as a pool for an import/manufacturing/export business.
&gt;
&gt; We have found that both solutions need initial parameters that are best
&gt; included in the training. As an example of the first problem we can
&gt; choose one nozzle. from a set of 10, that materially effect flow rate of
&gt; one component, but the nozzle can only be changed at plant maintenance
&gt; time. In the second example we&#39;re looking at a one or two time
&gt; constants. One of these effects the business cycle and should really be
&gt; arranged to fit several cycles into the accounting cycle.
&gt;
&gt; My question is...
&gt; Does MultiNEAT offer any way of adding such trainable parametric data to
&gt; the genome, without impinging directly on the network? I&#39;ve examined the
&gt; source code and found nothing obvious. Should I consider adding my own
&gt; flavour of a gene to sit alongside the network, and which implements its
&gt; own breeding and mutation?
&gt;
&gt; Rob Marsden
&gt;
&gt; 



